## Professional Services SEO Is Structurally Different

Solicitors, accountants, financial advisers, and management consultants operate in some of the most scrutinised search categories Google evaluates. The same algorithm that ranks a recipe blog does not treat a solicitor's website the same way — and it should not. Legal, financial, and healthcare content falls under what Google classifies as YMYL (Your Money or Your Life) — categories where harmful or low-quality information causes real-world damage.

The practical implication: Google applies significantly more weight to E-E-A-T (Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, Trustworthiness) signals in professional services searches than in almost any other commercial sector. A generic SEO approach — keyword-stuffed service pages, templated location content, thin blog posts — does not just underperform in these markets. It actively suppresses rankings because it fails to demonstrate the depth and credibility Google requires.

What works in professional services SEO is methodologically different: genuine topical authority built through comprehensive, expert-authored content; entity signals establishing practitioner and firm authority; technical precision resolving the infrastructure barriers common in law firm and accountancy websites; and local signals calibrated for the specific way professional services buyers search.

I work with solicitors, accountants, financial advisers, HR consultancies, and management consultancies across Reading, Berkshire, and nationally. Every engagement starts with understanding your specific regulatory environment and buyer behaviour before any tactic is applied.

