## Professional Services Sectors I Work With

### Solicitors and Law Firms

Legal SEO requires understanding how potential clients search across different practice areas — the way someone searches for a family solicitor differs structurally from how they search for a commercial property lawyer. Content strategy, local visibility, and practitioner entity authority must be calibrated to the specific practice area and client type.

I work with law firms across commercial, family, employment, property, and dispute resolution practices. Engagements typically focus on building topical authority in specific practice areas rather than attempting to cover all areas simultaneously.

### Accountancy and Finance

Accountancy firms serving SME and high-net-worth clients compete in a market where trust and expertise perception are the primary differentiators. Content that demonstrates genuine financial expertise — addressing the specific questions business owners ask about tax, accounts, and financial planning — builds the topical authority that drives organic enquiries.

I work with accountancy practices, financial advisory firms, and specialist tax consultancies on the content architecture and entity signals that establish verifiable expertise in highly competitive search markets.

### Management Consultancies and Professional Advisories

Strategy consultancies, HR consultancies, change management firms, and specialist advisories face a specific challenge: their services are complex, their buyers are sophisticated, and the research journey before a first conversation is extensive. SEO strategy for these businesses must address the full buyer journey — from early-stage problem awareness through to active provider comparison.

[B2B SEO](/services/b2b-seo/) methodology applies here: content clusters addressing the problems that drive buyers to consultancies, entity authority establishing the firm's specific areas of expertise, and technical foundations ensuring pages are visible when the right searches occur.

### Financial Advisory and Wealth Management

FCA-regulated firms face additional content compliance requirements alongside the standard E-E-A-T demands of financial services search. Content strategy must balance regulatory compliance with the genuine expertise demonstration that Google requires — a combination that most financial services SEO specialists do not navigate well.

